## DEC-002 — 2026-05-15 17:39 — Comment placement on structural lines is cursor-position-aware
**Iteration:** 1
**Decision:** When `⌘'` is pressed with an empty selection on a structural line (heading `#{1,6} `, list item `[-*+] ` or `\d+\. `, blockquote `> `), insertion location depends on cursor position: cursor in the marker zone (positions 0..N where N is the first text-char offset) → insert at end of the structural line with a leading space; cursor past the marker zone (text portion) → insert inline at cursor with a leading space if not already preceded by whitespace. Non-structural lines and non-empty selections retain existing behavior (multi-line selection → block-above; single-line selection → inline after selection). Outline-title parsing strips `<!-- ... -->` runs and the whitespace immediately preceding them.
**Rationale:** Preserves D-004's parsing-safety intent (no comment fragments the marker portion of a structural line) while allowing inline placement next to specific words in the text portion. Eliminates the all-structural-lines-block-above heuristic and the renderer's "collapse comment-only-line-above-structural" special case — comment-only lines always render as visible blank rows.
**Alternatives considered:**
  - All structural lines → block-above (D-004 prior interpretation) — rejected: prevents word-level inline placement on bullets/headings, and inserts a row above structural lines that disrupted icon-anchoring.
  - All structural lines → always EOL — rejected: loses inline-mid-text placement on bullets, which is desired for word-specific annotations.
  - Cursor-zone aware with marker-zone → above-line — rejected: solves parsing safety but still inserts a separate row that the renderer must collapse; EOL placement removes the entire collapse-heuristic surface area.
**Supersedes:** D-004
**Related:** AC8.1, AC8.2, AC12.5
**Context:** Surfaced during iteration-1 post-verify hand-testing; user reported the block-above icon-misalignment symptom and explicitly requested a redesign of structural-line comment placement.

