## DEC-005 — 2026-05-15 — Reader-first focus policy on document open
**Iteration:** 1
**Decision:** A document with non-trivial content opens with the editor scrolled to the top, the text view NOT first responder, and no caret visible. An empty document or a frontmatter-only document opens with the text view as first responder and the caret at offset 0 (empty) or just past the frontmatter close (frontmatter-only). Click on text content places the caret at the click point and makes the text view first responder. Programmatic moves (outline jump, sidebar card tap) take first responder and place the caret at the target. No in-session gesture is provided to leave the editing state back to no-cursor reading — reading state applies at document open only.
**Rationale:** The app is reader-first, editor-second. Opening to a blinking caret on the first heading (a) invites accidental keystrokes that would clobber the heading marker, (b) reveals the raw `#` markers in raw mode before the user has indicated they want to edit, and (c) implies an editing-first stance that contradicts the rendered-mode-as-primary UX. NSTextView always has an `NSRange` selection while it is first responder; "no cursor" can only be expressed as "not first responder." Empty / frontmatter-only documents are the explicit inverse: there is nothing to read, so the cursor's presence is an invitation to start typing.
**Alternatives considered:**
  - Always first responder, caret at offset 0 — rejected: produces the heading-clobber and raw-reveal problems described above.
  - Always first responder, caret restored from per-document persisted state — rejected: complicates document state, adds persistence surface, still has heading-clobber problem on first open.
  - Click-margin-inside-text-view to resign first responder — rejected: discoverability cost; standard NSTextView behavior is that clicking inside the text view places the caret. Departing from this convention without a clear UI signal would confuse users.
  - Esc key resigns first responder — rejected for this iteration: cheap and conventional, but the user explicitly accepted the v1 limitation that there is no in-session gesture to return to reading state. Can be revisited if reading/editing-state ambiguity becomes a real complaint.
**Related:** AC19.1, AC19.2, AC19.3, AC19.4, AC19.5
**Context:** Surfaced during Phase 3 re-run while reviewing the implications of the new gutter and current-line-highlight behavior. The user explicitly framed the app as "a markdown reader you can also edit and comment on cleanly," which drove the focus default.

