## DEC-006 — 2026-05-15 — Scroll anchoring on discrete mode and sidebar toggles
**Iteration:** 1
**Decision:** Mode toggle (raw ↔ rendered) and outline-sidebar toggle (open / close) preserve the user's vertical position via a one-shot anchor mechanism: the toggle handler captures `(anchorCharIndex, yOffsetWithinViewport)` BEFORE flipping the mode/sidebar state; `updateNSView` (or the equivalent layout-completion hook) consumes the token AFTER the layout pass and scrolls so the anchor's new fragment rect sits at the captured y-offset. The anchor character index = the cursor's logical-line start when the text view is first responder AND the cursor is within the visible rect; otherwise the topmost visible logical line's start (derived via `layoutManager.glyphRange(forBoundingRect: visibleRect, in: textContainer)`). Live window resize is NOT anchored — reflow during drag is acceptable.
**Rationale:** Raw and rendered modes use different fonts with different line heights; the same character offset lives at a substantially different y-position in each mode. Without anchoring, toggling modes can shift a user's focal content by hundreds of pixels (especially in docs with rendered headings, which are roughly 2× body height). The sidebar case is analogous: opening the outline narrows the text container, which can change line wrapping and shift vertical positions. A discrete one-shot mechanism (capture-on-action, consume-once) is preferable to a continuous watch — it avoids per-layout-pass bookkeeping and matches the user's mental model: "the toggle button keeps my place." Live window resize is left unanchored because the user is actively reshaping the window and visual reflow during drag is expected, not surprising.
**Alternatives considered:**
  - Match rendered and raw fonts more closely to minimize y-displacement — rejected: defeats the rendered-mode visual goals and constrains future theming.
  - Continuous focal-anchor that re-pins on every layout pass — rejected: per-frame work, harder to reason about, masks legitimate layout changes.
  - Anchor on live window resize (capture on `mouseDown` of resize, restore on `mouseUp`) — rejected for this iteration: tearing during drag, marginal benefit since the user is already engaged with a visual change.
  - Anchor only on the cursor's exact char index (no first-visible-line fallback) — rejected: fails for the reading case (per DEC-005, the text view is often not first responder) and for cases where the cursor is scrolled off-screen.
**Related:** AC20.1, AC20.2, AC20.3, AC20.4, AC20.5, AC16.1 (existing same-y preservation for in-mode highlight recompute — preserved, not superseded)
**Context:** Surfaced during Phase 3 re-run when the user pointed out that toggling to raw on a doc with rendered headings displaces the visible content significantly.

