## DEC-007 — 2026-05-15 — Raw-mode current-line highlight rendering
**Iteration:** 1
**Decision:** In raw mode, the logical line containing the caret is rendered with: (a) a tint band across the full text-container width in the text body, (b) a matching tint band across the gutter row, (c) the gutter label for that line rendered in bold. Tint = body color at 4% alpha (matching the existing AC14.5 blockquote tint intensity). In rendered mode the highlight is fully off. The highlight is also off when the text view is not first responder (i.e. when AC19's reading state applies).
**Rationale:** Editor-style current-line highlighting solves a real UX problem in raw mode — cursor re-location after taking eyes off the screen, or during arrow-key navigation in long monospace lines. Tinting both the gutter and the text row (Xcode style) provides redundant cues that anchor the eye immediately, vs. gutter-only tint (Sublime style) which solves only half the problem. Bolding the line label is a small additional cue that reads as "you are here." Disabled in rendered mode because the prose-reading visual would compete with the tint; disabled in reading state because there is no caret to highlight.
**Alternatives considered:**
  - Gutter-only tint, no bold (Sublime style) — rejected: requires the eye to dart back to the text to find the cursor; less effective.
  - Stronger tint (e.g. 8% alpha) — rejected for now: 4% is consistent with existing blockquote tint and reads as a clear-but-not-distracting cue. Tunable if needed.
  - Apply highlight in rendered mode as well — rejected: rendered mode is reader-oriented per DEC-005; a tinted line band would feel out of place.
**Related:** AC21.1, AC21.2, AC21.3, AC21.4, AC21.5
**Context:** Implemented as in-scope additional work during the Phase 3 re-run that delivered AC11.4 and AC11.5; user requested it explicitly while the gutter code was being touched.

